<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n12030g"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n12" href="#n12030g">N12 (VI.B.14)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n12all.htm#n12030g"> 30(g)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> chef des milices celestes</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">(<i>Le serpent de l&apos;Irlande</i>): La nuit suivante, apr&egrave;s une longue veille de pri&egrave;res, Ivor vit en songe l&apos;archange saint Michel. Celui-ci lui ordonna de faire porter, sans retard, au sanctuaire de pr&eacute;dilection qu&apos;il avait choisi au monde terrestre, les armes dont il s&apos;&eacute;tait servi pour mettre &agrave; mort le serpent. Mais, avant que l&apos;archev&ecirc;que n&apos;ait eu le temps de demander au <mark>chef des milices c&eacute;lestes</mark> le nom et le lieu du sanctuaire qui lui &eacute;tait agr&eacute;able entre tous, saint Michel disparut. <br><font color="green">[The next night, after a long wake of prayers, Ivor in a dream saw the Archangel Saint Michael. He ordered him, without delay, to bring the weapons that that had served him to kill the serpent to the sanctuary that he had chosen on earth. But, before the bishop had the time to ask the chief of the celestial armies for the name of the sanctuary that pleased above all others, Saint Michael disappeared.]</font> <small> &Eacute;tienne Dupont, <a name="LMSM" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#LMSM"><cite title="source">Les l&eacute;gendes du Mont-Saint-Michel</cite></a> (1924) 76</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
